of syncope in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neurocardiogenic reflex","Primary autonomic failure","Cardiac conduction defect","Volume depletion","Ventricular arrhythmia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECarotid sinus hypersensitivity induces syncope via an exaggerated baroreceptor reflex, classified as a \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurocardiogenic response\u003C/strong\u003E. Stimulation of the carotid sinus baroreceptors\u2014whether through external pressure, head movements, or tight collars\u2014leads to excessive vagal activation (cardioinhibitory response) and/or sympathetic withdrawal (vasodepressor response). This results in profound bradycardia, hypotension, and cerebral hypoperfusion, ultimately causing transient loss of consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary autonomic failure\u003C/strong\u003E involves impaired autonomic responses rather than exaggerated reflexes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac conduction defect\u003C/strong\u003E causes bradycardia through intrinsic cardiac electrical abnormalities\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolume depletion\u003C/strong\u003E causes syncope through reduced cardiac preload and cerebral perfusion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular arrhythmia\u003C/strong\u003E causes syncope through compromised cardiac output\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe carotid sinus reflex normally helps regulate blood pressure, but when hypersensitive, it can cause excessive bradycardia and vasodilation leading to cerebral hypoperfusion and syncope.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carotid sinus hypersensitivity causes syncope through an exaggerated baroreceptor reflex leading to bradycardia and vasodilation.","Neurocardiogenic syncope occurs when neural mechanisms trigger inappropriate vasodilation and bradycardia."],"references":["Kharsa A, Wadhwa R. Carotid Sinus Hypersensitivity. [Updated 2022 Oct 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559059/","Sutton R. Carotid sinus syndrome: Progress in understanding and management. Glob Cardiol Sci Pract. 2014 Jun 18;2014(2):1-8. doi: 10.5339/gcsp.2014.18. PMID: 25405171; PMCID: PMC4220427.","Runser LA, Gauer RL, Houser A. Syncope: Evaluation and Differential Diagnosis. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Mar 1;95(5):303-312. PMID: 28290647.","Grossman SA, Badireddy M. Syncope. 2023 Jun 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28723035."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16350"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67911"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T08:38:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T08:39:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9041"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82809"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":